reviewText:
We typically love Pete the Cat, and have all of the large books written by the original co-authors.  Unfortunately, since authorship has changed it seems the content of the Pete books has faded a bit.  While they're still fine as far as children's books go, the later books (including this one) seem to be missing some of the really imaginative, endearing qualities of the initial series.

There's not much content to this book really.  Pete goes to the beach.  He doesn't want to surf.  Then he ends up trying it.  There are none of the cute little phrases or quips that I've come to appreciate in Pete the Cat books.

The newer Pete stories, this one particularly, seem to be missing something.  Hopefully they'll be able to get back the charm that made Pete such a lovable character to begin with!
summary: NOT ONE OF THE BETTER PETE BOOKS
title: Pete the Cat: Pete at the Beach (My First I Can Read)

reviewText:
I read this because several girls in my class have read it, and some of them have come up to me pointing at a word or sentence and asking what it means, and um, yeah. It peaked my curiosity.

The book is really good, but not great. Definitely subject matter that some parents would need to be concerned about, but I think most kids who pick it up will be mature enough for it. You can definitely tell the author has some post-Modern influences, which is unusual to see in a YA novel, but the changing narrator and non-connected story line (at least at the beginning) work.

The ending was so stupid and such a cop out, though. It is insulting to the rest of the book. The whole book is real and dealing with issues, and you can think of how the book could in and be happy, but the author over does it. Throws in way too many things. And the happy ending you are wanting is ruined because there is just so much thrown into it.
summary: Definitely drew me in at first . . . then . . .

title: Counting by 7s

reviewText:
Willow is a genius who's observational skills and medical prowess make Sherlock Homes and House, MD look like amateurs. A lover of life, she is a gifted horticulturalist. What she's not so good at, however, is understanding how people work. Which is too bad because, having the particularly horrendous luck of being orphaned twice, she must now navigate through unimaginable pain and loss while unmoored to any particular community.

Except... maybe Willow does have more support than she first realizes, from the most unlikely sources: a taxi driver who thinks she's his guardian angel; an inept, angry guidance counselor; and a Vietnamese family who live in the garage behind their mother's nail salon.

Willow thinks so differently than most people that I can imagine some young readers will find her offputting... at first. But her quirks and logic are entirely endearing and soon begin to feel natural... to everyone, except Willow herself. Her first person narrative is divided by third-person glimpses at the people who's world she's changing... and who are changing her world.
This was a compulsive read - the 300-odd pages just sailed beneath my fingertips. Author Holly Goldberg Sloan does an amazing job of bringing the statistical anomaly that is Willow to life, and of making her feelings and actions seem realistic, while somehow retaining a lightness and hope even in Willow's darkest hours.

Willow might not resonate with every young reader, but to those she does, she will not soon be forgotten.
title: Counting by 7s

I don't like my kids to say things like: stupid, dumb, etc and these are Junie B's favorite words. She yells at adults, sasses her teacher and parents, and says mean things to friends. Her maturity level is equal to what my kids were at around 2 1/2. We are reading the books and using them as a learning tool of how NOT to behave and my kids give examples of what they could/should do instead. I would not allow my children to play with Junie B. if she were real!

title: Junie B. Jones's First Boxed Set Ever! (Books 1-4)

reviewText:
It breaks my heart to read these books with my four year old son. We received them as a gift and he is a voracious reader, so I can't find a way to discard the last two unread.

Junie B is supposed to be a 5 year old kindergarten student, but she speaks like a 1 or 2 year old and has a terrible time negotiating the world around her. Each story is jam-packed with painful grammar, awful behavior, and a fresh, spoiled attitude. The stories offer nothing to inspire the imagination and the plots seem to have been designed to undo all the lessons we've spent years teaching - most importantly, competence, confidence and respect for others!

Once we've finished them, these books will disappear! I can't imagine any educator recommending them, and I can't imagine allowing him to continue in any program that believes they are enriching reading.
title: Junie B. Jones's First Boxed Set Ever! (Books 1-4)

reviewText:
I LOVE Junie B. Jones because my daughter and I laugh out loud as we read the series. She has her own unique voice and extremely funny personality that has my kids engaged in reading.

BUT I must tell you I HATE that Junie B. a Kindergartener, has such bad manners, is sassy and that she often speaks in broken English that is more like a 3 year old than a child 5 or 6. I think that for kids learning to read, the misspelled words can be confusing.  I often have to stop and make sure my kids know that Junie B. is acting naughty and although we are laughing because she is funny- that type of behavior is NOT acceptable.

So my review for Junie B....will have to B love/hate- 3 star sorry Junie B.  But until you learn better manners, I can't give you any more stars.
summary: Junie B. Jones- It's a LOVE HATE relationship
title: Junie B. Jones's First Boxed Set Ever! (Books 1-4)

reviewText:
She was elusive. She was today. She was tomorrow. She was the faintest scent of a cactus flower, the flitting shadow of an elf owl. We did not know what to make of her. In our minds we tried to pin her to a cork board like a butterfly, but the pin merely went through and away she flew.

I read this years ago and have waited until the right time to share the Stargirl experience with my daughter. Everyone should take a page from her book and be less like them; the masses that don't realize how truly alone they are. A must read and ponder for everyone.
summary: In our minds we tried to pin her to a cork board like a butterfly
title: Stargirl (Stargirl Series)

reviewText: Stargirl, is about a girl who is weird, different, and definetly NOT normal. In a way though, she is much more down to earth and kind than all of us combined, even if she can get a little carried away. How does she know your birthday or that you like porcupine neckties? The mystery of why the way she is and how she knows wh at she knows will keep you wondering. "Star people are rare. You'll be lucky to see another." The wise words of Archie will keep you thinking. "a chilling isolation. NO one spoke to us. No one nodded to us. No one smiled at us. No one looked at us." The heat of the hotseat and the hate torward Stargirl will have you hooked. Stargirl by  Jerry Spinelli is a book that you definetly should have on your wish list.

reviewText:
Wasn't awful. But there were enough annoying discrepancies and nonsensical situations to bug me a little bit. I'm also not very keen on entire stories built around a mysterious event that needs to be solved in the cliffhanger way at the end. The whole thing required a little more suspension of disbelief than I am able to deliver.  I almost skipped to the end to confirm my thoughts about the mystery so that I could end reading it early.

I am of the opinion that a good book is a journey for which the story is the destination. This book gives you a little tidbit of info, then kinda drags you through a story so that you can get to the destination, which is the ending, not the story itself.

The whole thing left me kind of "meh"...

reviewText:
I love Brandon Sanderson - he's a great writer with some impressive work to show for it. I like the premise of Steelheart - it's a great story, but I absolutely hate how he wrote it. Usually, the golden rule in writing is "show, don't tell" - Sanderson does the exact opposite in this book. Everything is written like the protagonist is reading it from a book or holding a speech, it gets annoying really quick (and all from the perspective of a teenage kid *sigh*). Maybe it is because it is a YA novel, yet I have read plenty of other YA novels that don't have this problem.

The story is great however, it's got some surprising twists, and is well thought of. I will probably read the sequal for the sake of the story, but it is going to be hard work getting through it.
title: Steelheart (The Reckoners)

reviewText:
very rarely is the movie better than the book . Anyone who knows me can agree that I LOVE the movies . In this case it is . The book better than the movie . The Hunger Games is one of those books that the movie will leave a lot of unanswered questions and reading the book fills those holes . Being that I saw the movie long before reading the book , I enjoyed it for the most part except until the end Katniss seemed whiny and childish . She's supposed to be 16 & the sole provider for her family . Example , during the games Katniss being severely upset with the death of Foxface . Sad , yes , that they are put in that situation but the sad reality is that only ONE could live .

May the odds be ever in your favor !

During the games , every chapter is hunting and hunting , filling my canteen , more hunting , sleeping in my sleeping bag oh yes and hunting . OMG enough already , there was more survival over conversation . We get it , I understood the need to eat , with it being the HUNGER games !! Extremely drawn out scenes and extremely boring scenes . More interesting stuff , the moat annoying and unnerving part of the book was probably Katniss's unlikable whining . Why I continued to read it is beyond me because I DID like it !!! But I loved the movie so much with my obsession with it that I had to continue reading !! Yes , some of the scenes are far better read on screen than in paper but that's just on the imagination of movie makers . I can see this being ons of those awful books that are included in required reading in school . Except not so awful . An instant classic .

reviewText:
That is, until I was at a party and two of my friends gave the Harry Potter saga such a ringing endorsement that I was convinced I was missing out. I picked up the fourth book and was determined to read it, to reconsider my stance on the series.

I quickly got through 200 pages, but it was then that I came to the same crisis I always do when reading a Harry Potter book: Do I really want to go on?

And as always, the answer was no. So in keeping with my MO that "Life is too short to read books you're not interested in," I put it down and have no regrets.

Sorry, Harry and the gang, I just have no interest in you or your adventures. I guess I never really "got" this phenomenon, and that's OK with me. There are better books out there.
summary: So after suffering through the first three books of this series, I vowed never to carry on and finish it.
title: Harry Potter And The Goblet Of Fire

reviewText:
With all of the hype surrounding Harry Potter, I would bet that many people will pass over these books as nothing more than a fad. That would be unfortunate.  I was one of the people who bought them on a whim. I was taking a friend of mine to the Atlanta airport, when I noticed "Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire" on the shelf at a bookstore. Knowing that they would fly off the shelves if I didn't grab a copy (I had heard about the book on the news that evening), I bought a copy. Not only that, but I bought a copy of each of them (I'm one of those people who, in the heat of the moment, believes that if I don't get one now, I'll never be able to!)
I decided I would give them to my 8 year old niece for Christmas. Now, I heard the stories about how "evil" the books were supposed to be, so I decided to read the first one - just to see. I was HOOKED.
I read all the books the week I bought them. I gave my niece a card and $20.00 for Christmas.
Sure, these books may be the epitome of mass market publication. And you might get sick of seeing Harry Potter everywhere. But when it comes down to it, the books are good. Ignore the trinkets, the bookends, posters, glasses, stuffed animals and all the hype. Buy the books. take it from this 30+ year old kid - they are every bit as enjoyable as they are made out to be.
title: Harry Potter And The Goblet Of Fire

reviewText: This book is not quite as satisfying as books 1, 2, and 3. (I thought 2 better than 1 and 3 better than 2.) This is for three reasons.  Most importantly, the 20 pages in which the book reaches its climax is going to  frighten the younger members of the core audience.  It's like a Stephen  King novel for those 20 pages.  Additionally, I found the first 150 pages  or so annoying because, although I suppose necessary, they delayed the  characters from getting to Hogswart's.  Finally, be warned this book  doesn't come to a satisfactory conclusion like the first 3 -- things are  left very much "in progress".
summary: Flawed, but still a 5 star effort

reviewText:
Like the last book, The Order of the Phoenix gives Harry more serious problems than the first novels - he's 15 now. In the last book he saw Voldemort return and a student die, so of course he's still upset about that, and he finds himself with a host of other problems in this new book - including the nasty OWL exams.
Some of the characters seem to be acting rather oddly at the start, but this is all explained by the end of the book.
The book is a bit longer than it could have been, and it does get a bit bogged down in Harry's teen angst/worries, but what fan of the series would want a shorter book?
Yay Harry!
summary: Good, but quite long and more serious

title: The Invention of Hugo Cabret

reviewText: So yeah, the illustrations were neat.  Yes, I highly liked the design and the color of the pages.  But the story itself?  Overrated.  Nothing much happens.  The passages are short.  At the end of the book, it's revealed that the entire story is based on a real person, really ruining the book for me.  It started out really powerfully and you think, hey, this might actually be a neat, slightly supernatural mystery, but nope, all you've got is a boring book about artists and film-makers.  It took only half an hour to read, and the majority of the book just had me flipping through pictures, when I had expected it to be an "illustrated" book as in 'there are small images maybe once per chapter.'  This had such potential, and I'm having lots of trouble understanding all the hype surrounding it.  Not as tremendous as it should have, could have, and is portrayed to be.
title: The Invention of Hugo Cabret

reviewText: I read the first two books to my 9 year old son.  We each loved them.  I decided to let him read the 3rd book on his own, "Curse of the Warmbloods."  It had some flesh-eating mites or fleas that would swarm it's prey and de-flesh it in moments.  This so scared my son that he could not sleep for a couple of long nights.  I love the Underland world that the author created and the quests and the characters, however, I think she needed to keep in mind that some material may be unsuitable for younger readers.  Still, my son says he'll continue with the 4th book and also the 5th.  :)

reviewText:
This book is nicely huge and has perforated pages that make it easy to remove a page if you want kiddo to work independently without writing in the entire book. I have a three year old that has never really been exposed to work pages before but she was very excited when I pulled this from the box and she couldn't wait to work on it... I helped her through a few of the trace mazes and she tried. She did get frustrated after a few pages because I would insist that she try to stay within the line and not just draw a straight line from place to place, but she will learn.
I do suggest that if your child isn't familiar with this type of stuff that you walk them through a few times before letting them try on their own.
title: School Zone - Big Preschool Workbook - Ages 4 and Up, Colors, Shapes, Numbers 1-10, Alphabet, Pre-Writing, Pre-Reading, and Phonics (Big Get Ready Workbook)

reviewText:
Wow, I can't believe I used to like this series. While bored, I picked this book off my shelf to try and reread it. I'm shocked that the word "SKANK" is used in this book!

Nikki claims to be a dork. I actually snorted. She is just like MacKenzie, the clich mean girl. Both are rude, care way too much about looks and try their best to get the attention of a sweet, kind boy who I hope ends up with someone else when he is older.

The most apalling quotes? "You FAT, worthless WANNA-BES!" and "Don't you need a LICENSE to be that UGLY?" Cringe. 9-year-olds should not be reading this.

Isn't it terrible to have a daughter you love but is TERRIBLE to you? That's Nikki. I rolled my eyes when she called MacKenzie rude, because that is also the word to describe Nikki.
title: Dork Diaries 1: Tales from a Not-So-Fabulous Life

reviewText:
I picked this book up on a whim, curious to see if it was anything like the vastly popular Wimpy Kid books, and to my joy it was.  Written as the diary of a middle school girl, Dork Diaries chronicles Nikki's days as she navigates the ups and downs of a new school, embarrassing parents, and an adorably quirky little sister.

Filled with fun illustrations, and fonts that keep you looking, Rachel Renee Russell has created for girls what Jeff Kinney did for boys with his Wimpy Kids series.
summary: Diary of a Wimpy Kid for girls!
title: Dork Diaries 1: Tales from a Not-So-Fabulous Life

reviewText: My son who is ten years old enjoyed the book.  As a parent too I was happy that it was a realistic story and exposes some of the bullying threats that may happen in a school in not the typical simplistic way but with all the complexities of life and friendship - and then it had a good ending where the characters made the right choices...it also deals with the theme of being a new kid in an unfamiliar school.  The ninja element of course created all the excitement, and I liked the little bit of fantasy feel that the book has.  I read this book to my two kids at bedtime, and I did skip over one or two rather gross fighting and blood descriptions...that was a little too violent for me.  I will give the next book a try though...hard to find good books that interest boys.  They just don't like the fairy stuff...
